Exploration & Clustering of Crime in Louisville

Delores Mincarelli

2023-05-31

Motivation

I moved to Louisville in 2022 and decided to put my datascience skills to use by exploring public data. A few high profile crime incidents propelled me to explore crime in the place I now call home.

Conclusions:

Insights from exploring the data:
  • What day do most crimes occur? I thought that weekends would have higher crime volume than weekdays, but, it turned out that volume each day of the week is nearly equivalent.
  • Which hour do most crimes occur? Midnight was the highest, but I was surprised that noon was a close second.
  • The influx of tourists for the Kentucky Derby in May did not cause a spike in crime.
  • Assault was the most common type of crime, and most crimes occurred in the home vs outside or in commercial entities.
Insights from Clustering
  • I chose to cluster the data based on zip code and the type of crime, like Assault or Theft.
  • Because each zip code has a different number of residents, I normalized the data by evaluating the percent of crime type rather than the number of each crime type.
  • Three clusters represented the data well, with one of the clusters having only one zip code. This particular zip code had a high prevalence of sex crimes which distinguished it from all other zip codes. The other two clusters differed in the percent of Assault crimes.

Cleaning, Feature Engineering

I used the date and time that a crime occurred to add additional features like month, weekday, and hour.

lville_crime_select_tbl <- lville_crime_raw_tbl %>% 
    filter(city == "LOUISVILLE" & year(as_datetime(date_occured))== 2022 & nchar(zip_code)==5) %>% 
    mutate(
          count_me      = 1,
          pm_vs_am_flag = as.numeric(pm(as_datetime(date_occured))),
          weekday_flag  = ifelse(weekdays(as_datetime(date_occured)) %in% c("Saturday", "Sunday"),0, 1),
          premise_type  = premise_type %>% str_trim(),
          hour_of_day   = hour(as_datetime(date_occured)),
          month_of_year = as_factor(month(as_datetime(date_occured), label = TRUE )),
          day_of_week   = as_factor(wday(as_datetime(date_occured),  label = TRUE )),
          day_of_month  = day(as_datetime(date_occured))
          ) %>% 
    select(
          count_me
        , date_occured
        , zip_code
        , weekday_flag
        , hour_of_day
        , month_of_year
        , day_of_week
        , day_of_month
        , pm_vs_am_flag
        , crime_type
        , uor_desc
        , premise_type 
    ) %>% 
    glimpse()

Identify and remove zipcodes with less than 10 crimes

The data for these zips is likely incomplete.

remove_zips <- lville_crime_select_tbl %>% 
                select( count_me
                        , zip_code) %>% 
                group_by(zip_code) %>% 
                summarize(count_of_crimes = sum(count_me)) %>% 
                filter(count_of_crimes < 10) %>% 
                distinct(zip_code) %>% 
                pull()

lville_crime_select_tbl <- lville_crime_select_tbl %>% 
                            filter(!(zip_code %in% remove_zips))

Exploratory Data Analysis

Function for bar charts

# The enquo() function is short for "enquoting,"
# By using enquo(), we can capture the column name provided as an argument in the function call and use it later within the dplyr pipeline without immediately evaluating it.
# The quo_name() function is used to extract the name of a quosure object. It takes a quosure as an argument and returns the name of the expression as a character string.
# Together, enquo() and quo_name() allow us to capture and manipulate unevaluated expressions
# They are part of tidyverse

bar_plot_function <- function(df, group_col, n = NULL) {
  group_col <- enquo(group_col)  # Capture the column name as a quosure
  
  df %>%
    select(count_me, !!group_col) %>%
    group_by(!!group_col) %>%
    summarise(count_crimes = sum(count_me)) %>%
    mutate(col_group = !!group_col %>% as_factor() %>% fct_reorder(count_crimes)) %>%
    filter(if (!is.null(n)) rank(desc(count_crimes), ties.method = "min") <= n else TRUE) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = col_group, y = count_crimes, fill = "#2c3e50")) +
    geom_col() +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_tq() +
    theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),  # Remove horizontal gridlines
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
    labs(title = paste0("Crimes in 2022 by ", quo_name(group_col)),
         subtitle = if (!is.null(n)) paste0("Showing the top ", n)) +
    xlab(NULL) +
    ylab("Count of Crimes") +
    scale_fill_identity()
}

Function for line charts

line_plot_function <- function(df, group_col, n = NULL, xlabel = NULL, sub_title = NULL) {
  group_col <- enquo(group_col)  # Capture the column name as a quosure

    
  df %>%
    select(count_me, !!group_col) %>%
    group_by(!!group_col) %>%
    summarise(count_crimes = sum(count_me)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = !!group_col, y = count_crimes )) +
    geom_line(linewidth = 2, linetype = 1, color = "#2c3e50") +
    theme_tq() +
    theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),  # Remove horizontal gridlines
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
    labs(title = paste0("Crimes in 2022 by ", quo_name(group_col)),
         subtitle = sub_title ) +
    xlab(xlabel) +
    ylab("Count of Crimes") +
    scale_fill_identity()
}

Function for column chart

col_plot_function <- function(df, group_col,  xlabel = NULL, sub_title = NULL) {
  group_col <- enquo(group_col)  # Capture the column name as a quosure

    
  df %>%
    select(count_me, !!group_col) %>%
    group_by(!!group_col) %>%
    summarise(count_crimes = sum(count_me)) %>%
    ggplot() +
    geom_col(aes(x = !!group_col, y = count_crimes ), fill = "#2c3e50") +
    theme_tq() +
    theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),  # Remove horizontal gridlines
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
    labs(title = paste0("Crimes in 2022 by ", quo_name(group_col)),
         subtitle = sub_title ) +
    xlab(xlabel) +
    ylab("Count of Crimes") 

}

Prepare Data for clustering, focusing on zip and crime type

We will normalize the data by getting the proportion of each type by zip

K-means clustering is a popular unsupervised machine learning algorithm used for partitioning a dataset into a predefined number of clusters. The goal of k-means clustering is to group similar data points together and minimize the intra-cluster variance.
The algorithm works by iteratively assigning data points to the nearest cluster centroid and updating the centroids based on the newly assigned points.
lville_crime_grouped_tbl <- lville_crime_select_tbl %>% 
    select( count_me
           ,zip_code
           ,crime_type) %>% 
    group_by(zip_code, crime_type)%>%
    summarize(sum_crimes = sum(count_me)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    
    # Proportion
    group_by(zip_code) %>%
    mutate(prop_of_total = sum_crimes / sum(sum_crimes)) %>%
    ungroup() 
    
    head(lville_crime_grouped_tbl)

Create k-means function, using nstart = 100 and default of 3 clusters

kmeans_mapper <- function(centers = 3) {
    set.seed(42)
    zip_crime_mtx %>%
        kmeans(centers = centers, nstart = 100)
}

Prep for Skree Plot

Run K-Means for different cluster counts so we can evaluate within sum-of-squares

This will inform our decision on the number of clusters to use

# Here, we are creating tibble with one column called "centers", and providing 15 values
# which will be provided to kmeans_mapper function
# glance() pulls data elements from the k_means object, like "centers" and "tot.withinss"

kmeans_mapped_tbl <- tibble(centers = 1:15) %>%
mutate(k_means = centers %>% map(kmeans_mapper)) %>%
mutate(glance  = k_means %>% map(glance))


kmeans_mapped_tbl %>%
    unnest(glance) %>%
    select(centers, tot.withinss)

Skree Plot

Plot cluster number and within sum-of-squares, to help choose number of clusters

kmeans_mapped_tbl %>%
    unnest(glance) %>%
    select(centers, tot.withinss) %>%
    
    # Visualization
    ggplot(aes(centers, tot.withinss)) +
    geom_point(color = "#2c3e50", size = 4) +
    geom_line(color = "#2c3e50", linewidth = 1) +
    ggrepel::geom_label_repel(aes(label = centers), color = "#2c3e50") + 
    
    # Formatting
    theme_tq() +
    labs(
        title = "Skree Plot",
        subtitle = "Measures the distance each of the zip codes are from the closest K-Means center",
        caption = "Conclusion: Based on the Skree Plot, we select 3 clusters to segment zip codes."
    )

Use 3 clusters and prepare to use umap() to visualize results

umap() is a dimensionality reduction technique commonly used for visualizing high-dimensional data in two dimensions

umap_obj <- zip_crime_mtx %>%
    umap()

umap_results_tbl <- umap_obj$layout %>%
    as_tibble() %>%
    set_names(c("x", "y")) %>%
    bind_cols(
        zip_crime_tbl %>% select(zip_code)
    )


# # ---------------------------------------------------------
# #Use K-Means to Add Cluster Assignments ----
# # ---------------------------------------------------------

# # from kmeans_mapped_tbl, which has 1 to 15 centers and the kmeans object, we want to use
# # 3 clusters, so pull the k_means col, and pluck the 3rd row from the tibble for 3 clusters
# # result is the  kmeans object

kmeans_3_obj <- kmeans_mapped_tbl %>%
    pull(k_means) %>%
    pluck(3)

# add orig dataset to it to get zip code
kmeans_3_clusters_tbl <- kmeans_3_obj %>%
    augment(zip_crime_tbl) %>%
    select(zip_code, .cluster)

# join to umap on zip
umap_kmeans_3_results_tbl <- umap_results_tbl %>%
    left_join(kmeans_3_clusters_tbl)

Define Each Cluster

Join cluster assignment from K-Means back to original dataset

zip_crime_cluster_tbl <- lville_crime_select_tbl %>% 
    select( zip_code
           ,crime_type
           ,count_me) %>% 
    left_join(kmeans_3_clusters_tbl) %>% 
    group_by(.cluster, crime_type) %>% 
    summarize(count_me = sum(count_me)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    # Calculate Proportion of Total
    group_by(.cluster) %>%
    mutate(prop_of_total = count_me /sum(count_me)) %>%
    mutate(prop_of_total = round(prop_of_total,3)*100.00) %>% 
    ungroup()

# Add to the plot
cluster_label_loc <- umap_kmeans_3_results_tbl |>
    group_by(.cluster) |>
    summarize(x = min(x) - 0.1, y = max(y) - 0.1) |>

# Then add to the plot:
